storians, anthropologists, and archeologists, these lively essays take us from Mayan states to twentieth-century Benin in Nigeria, to the palace of Japanese Shoguns, the Chinese Imperial courts, eighteenth-century Versailles, Mughal India, and beyond. Together they investigate how women's roles differed, how their roles changed over time, and how their histories can illuminate the structures of power and societies in which they lived. This work also furthers our understanding of how royal courts, created to project the authority of male rulers, maintained themselves through the reproductive and productive powers of women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCourtesansxHistory. 0aCourts and courtiersxHistory. 0aFavorites, RoyalxHistory. 0aHaremsxHistory. 0aLadies-in-waitingxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aafrican royal harem.  aanthropology.  aarcheology.  aattendants.  aaztec royalty.  abenin.  achinese imperial courts.  aconcubines.  adrudges.  aentertainers.  afrench royalty.  agender and power.  agender studies.  aglobal history.  ahistory.  ahuman history.  ajapanese shogun.  amaids.  amale rulers.  amayan states.  amen and women.  amonarchy.  amothers.  amughal india.  anigeria.  anobility.  aofficials.  apatriarchal society.  aproductive power.  areproductive power.  aroyal courts.  aroyalty.  asex.  aversailles.  awives.  awomen in royal courts.  aworld history.1 aAndaya, Barbara Watson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossler, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Susan Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaboush, JaHyun Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHisako, H